rp in the Highlands; and a translation of a French work of music theory. The list of his unrealised publications is even longer, including a proof of the oriental origins of the Scots. He married Anne Young, a well-known Edinburgh piano teacher, and his letters cast new light on the circumstances and date of her death. Taking account of Gunn's diverse experiences as a musician-scholar in Cambridge, London and Edinburgh, studying his sundry occupations, and exploring his social connections through a recently unearthed cache of his letters, this study moves away from 'treatise archaeology' and offers a broader view than is usually possible with such figures. The book will be of interest to those studying historical performance practice, music education in Enlightenment Britain, and the dissemination of Enlightenment thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  aAntiquarian.  aCello Treatise.  aEighteenth Century.  aEnlightenment Thought.  aEnlightenment.  aEuropean Influence.  aFigured Bass.  aFlute.  aHighland Harp.  aHistorical Performance Practice.  aJohn Gunn.  aMusic Education.  aMusic Theory.  aMusical Topics.  aMusician.  aPiano.  aProgress.  aRational Thought.  aScholar.  aScottish Cellist.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800103696423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800103696/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles